    <p><strong>Hillas (1984)</strong> introduced the iconic size–magnetic-field diagram (the "Hillas plot") that provides order-of-magnitude estimates for the maximum energy to which a source can accelerate particles, based on its size and magnetic field strength. The Hillas criterion remains a fundamental benchmark in cosmic-ray astrophysics.</p>

    <h2>Relevance to ArXiv Atlas</h2>
    <p>Cited by <WikiLink slug="pages/2603.16647" text="Peretti et al. (2603.16647)" /> for the Hillas-type confinement argument used to estimate E<sub>max</sub> at <WikiLink slug="pages/recollimation-shocks" text="recollimation shocks" /> in sub-relativistic jets.</p>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/particle-acceleration-basics" text="Particle acceleration basics" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/diffusive-shock-acceleration" text="Diffusive shock acceleration" /></li>
    </ul>
  </main>
</Base>
